        </div>
        <div class= "span5 copy">
          <p> <!-- Marketing Section 1 -->
          Real money direct into the electricity user's email inbox for doing &quot;Nothing&quot;.
          This statement is not completely true, but by being a Power Company's insurer of last resort can be very profitable. 
          Some power, automatically switched off at the Electricity Customer's premises, is sold back to the Power Companies during a crisis or daily peak demand.  
          This has great value when priced at the marginal cost of generating it or the cost of outages (non-voluntary load shedding). 
          The Power Companies do not have this power available on such short notice and/or they use very expensive methods to generate it.
          This virtual power sold back to the suppliers, ensures grid stability, and thus critical systems and lights stay on.
          It becomes vital with tidal-, solar voltaic- or wind-generators, to compensate for sudden changes in the supply and grid overload conditions.
          The above is &quot;real&quot; grid capacity that will never need building and is therefore the greenest power around.
          The Power Companies will lease this capacity/insurance (initially for 3 years) to be used at their discretion (with fixed limits to manage potential monopolistic abuse.).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row-fluid section2">
        <div class="span5 offset1 copy copy-right">
          <p>
          This model is different from the smart-grid systems (smart-meter and other Virtual Power Stations) in that the client immediately receives something 
          substantial back for the inconvenience of waiting a bit or being slightly away from the optimal temperature. 
          With smart-grid systems all the money stays with the Power Companies and all the inconvenience stays with the much smaller client; a very monopolistic relation.  
          Other historical penalties like maximum demand charges, time of use - and/or dynamic tariffs, have had limited success, resulting mostly in higher energy prices.
          It is very difficult for a Power Company's clients to understand, monitor and control energy consumption as a highly educated person is needed to understand the implications, accounts and tariffs. (? by design)
          With Cloud Power no customer intervention is required, the inconvenience is very limited and all transactions are very transparent and real-time.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="span5 asset">
          <img class="img-polaroid" src="http://esw4.co.za/static/cloud_connect.gif" alt = "Energy flow and Cloud connections">
          <figcaption>Cloud connections schematic</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row-fluid section3">
        <div class="span5 offset1 asset">
          <img class="img-polaroid" src="http://esw4.co.za/static/cloud_customers.jpg"  alt = "Cloud Power Customer">
          <figcaption>Potential Cloud Power Customers</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="span5 copy">
          <p> <!-- trageting -->
          Commercial buildings consume between 10% and 20% of a country's electricity and most of this energy use is not directly linked to production. 
          The Cloud Power Green Energy model targets HVAC systems in these buildings because they use up to 60% of the building's electrical energy and already have centralised control systems.
          These systems are always on to maintain the internal environment and will allow fast partial switch-off, for a limited time, with low adverse effects.
          The buildings inherently have some buffer capacity (thermodynamics) and the temperatures recover fast after HVAC systems are switched back to full capacity. 
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
