            <div class="accordion-group">
              <div class="accordion-heading">
                <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseZero">
                  What is Bitcoin?
                </a>
              </div>
              <div id="collapseZero" class="accordion-body collapse">
                <div class="accordion-inner">
                  Internet currency (an encrypted series of numbers) that exists solely on the internet to enable trade with very little costs.  
                  It is stored in a Bitcoin wallet on your computer (with backup of the codes on your USB drive) and can be transferred to anyone, anywhere, instantaneous over the net. 
                  There are physical exchanges where it can easily be exchanged to most currencies.  
                  Example:  In this scenario the Power Company buys Bitcoin with physical currency and pays this out over time for the standby function, insurance and energy bought.  
                  Cloud Power receives this daily and immediately pass most of it on to our client generators.  
                  The clients can then partial pay their electricity accounts with Bitcoin, completing the circle in a very transparent and market oriented way.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
              <div class="accordion-heading">
                <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseOne">
                  What does BMS and HVAC stand for?
                </a>
              </div>
              <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-body collapse">
                <div class="accordion-inner">
                  Building Management System (also SCADA; Supervisory Control And Data Acquisition) and Heating Ventilation and Air-Conditioning.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
              <div class="accordion-heading">
                <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseTwo">
                  Why is this model so green?
                </a>
              </div>
              <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-body collapse">
                <div class="accordion-inner">
                  This type of system is grid stabilizing because of its nearly instantaneous response to any request for extra energy. 
                  The Power Companies need less generators on standby/idle to continuous supply the demand and less generating plant need to be build and/or only the cleanest type of generator run.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
              <div class="accordion-heading">
                <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseThree">
                  Why must the grid supply exactly match the demand?
                </a>
              </div>
              <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-body collapse">
                <div class="accordion-inner">
                  The energy generated in the grid (network) must exactly balance the sum of the energy losses and demand as energy cannot be destroyed or created, it just changes from one form to another. 
                  If the generated energy is higher, the generators all speed up causing the frequency and voltage of the grid to increase. 
                  When it is lower the frequency and voltage decreases as the generators cannot keep up and thus slow down. 
                  As all electric motors run at, or nearly at, the same frequency they also speed up or slow down causing the demand to decrease or increase.
                  The runaway condition that ensues is the grid instability. 
                  The Power Companies mitigate this by disconnecting some generating capacity or some demand respectively from the grid, both undesired and expensive.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
              <div class="accordion-heading">
                <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseFour">
                  What is a Virtual Power Station?
                </a>
              </div>
              <div id="collapseFour" class="accordion-body collapse">
                <div class="accordion-inner">
                  Combination of many small suppliers in one pool such that it can be monitored and controlled as easily as current Power Stations.
                  Instead of generating more power on the grid, the same effect on grid stability can be attained by trimming the demand. 
                  Thus &quot;negative demand&quot; is exactly the same as &quot;positive supply&quot; to balance the &quot;supply = demand&quot; equation.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-group">
              <div class="accordion-heading">
                <a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2" href="#collapseFive">
                  What is in it for the electricity customer and Cloud Power Green Energy?
